{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = Princess | name = Kiki Bokassa | honorific_suffix = | image = <!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = Marie-Ange Bokassa<ref name="Nordlinger">{{cite book|last1=Nordlinger|first1=Jay|title=Children of Monsters: An Inquiry into the Sons and Daughters of Dictators|date=22 Sep 2015|publisher=Encounter Books|isbn=9781594038167}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1975}} | birth_place = [[Paris]], France | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = [[Expressionist]] | movement = | spouse = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }} Princess '''Kiki Bokassa''' (born 1975, [[Paris|Paris, France]])<ref name="iloubnan2011">[http://iloubnan.info/en/detail/16/61649 ''"Dieci", a new exhibition by Kiki Bokassa in Beirut''], iloubnan.info, May 16, 2011. Retrieved 2012-02-06.</ref> is an [[autodidact]] [[conceptual artist]], who works in the [[expressionist]], [[figurative art]] genre.<ref name="iloubnan2011" /><ref name="mural08">[http://www.executive-bulletin.com/news.dtl.php?news_id=2840 ''Bokassa's Mural signing ceremony''], Executive Company Bulletin, November 18, 2008.</ref> She has paintings in private collections in the [[Persian Gulf]] and USA.<ref name="mural08" /> She was brought up in [[Lebanon]] and has exhibited widely in [[Beirut]] and overseas.<ref name="iloubnan2011" />
In April 2009, Bokassa created an immersive art event in [[Beirut]] entitled ‘72 hrs’, in which she painted for 72 hours continuously as a peaceful form of expression in self-imposed [[incarceration]]. The work took place in a giant canvas cube at Laboratoire d'Art. The event came to the attention of more than 30 international [[mass media|media]] outlets and was reported in at least 74 countries.<ref name="iloubnan2011" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Culture/Arts/Apr/25/Living-under-public-scrutiny-with-life-emulating-art.ashx#axzz1TXOSLSSv|title=Living under public scrutiny with life emulating art |last=Mosley|first=Matthew |date=25 April 2009|publisher=[[Daily Star (Lebanon)|Daily Star]] |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>
She is the daughter of Emperor of the [[Central African Empire]] [[Jean-Bédel Bokassa]].<ref name="Nordlinger" />
